                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\">\n                                        <placeName>Charleston</placeName>\n                                        <date>Aug. 18. 1851</date>\n                              </p>\n                              <p>Rev<lb/>\n                                        <addressee>Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(2)\">Dr. Sir</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(3)\">I received your letter and<lb/> the proof sheets\n                                        of my Manuscript this<lb/> morning, and hasten to transmit\n                                        it back<lb/> to you with a few slight corrections.\n                                                  All<add>?</add><lb/> with my thanks for your\n                                        promptness<lb/> and impartiality which you have evinced\n                                        in<lb/> the matter.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">Your letter explanatory of the insertion<lb/> of\n                                                  <persName>Mr. Newman's</persName> article is quite\n                                        satisfactory.<lb/> Indeed your whole letter is so; and\n                                        reads<lb/> like the emanation of a good and just man.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">You are mistaken as to the impression<lb/> imbibed\n                                        here in consequence of your remarks<lb/> on the controversy\n                                        about <persName>Mr Poznanski</persName> &amp; the\n                                                  <persName>Rev<lb/> Dr Eckman</persName>. If your\n                                        argument is bad<lb/> in that matter, it is because your\n                                        premises<lb/> were rotten. And we found fault with<lb/> your\n                                        drawing conclusions not warranted<lb/> by facts. But still\n                                        the discussion was fair<lb/> and honorable; gentlemanly and\n                                        just. If<lb/> you do not convince your opponents you\n                                        never<lb/> offend them. A spirit of truth and tolerance</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3445hz65/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
